    <question>
        <prompt>The Sacco and Vanzetti case demonstrated:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Fair treatment of immigrants</option>
            <option letter="b">Anti-immigrant and anti-radical prejudices</option>
            <option letter="c">Support for labor unions</option>
            <option letter="d">Effectiveness of the justice system</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The trial and execution of Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti, Italian immigrant anarchists, demonstrated the strong anti-immigrant and anti-radical prejudices of the 1920s. Despite questionable evidence and worldwide protests, they were convicted of murder and executed. Their case became a symbol of nativism and political intolerance, revealing biases against both immigrants and radical political beliefs in the American justice system.</explanation>
